<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910605-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>910605-0010.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Prospects Dim for EC Move   To Ban All Tobacco Ads</HL><DATE>06/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AND SERVICES (HOU)TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)</IN><RE>DENMARK (DA)EUROPEAN COMMUNITY (EC)EUROPE (EU)GERMANY (GE)NETHERLANDS (NL)SCANDINAVIA (SCA)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   LUXEMBOURG (AP) -- A proposal for a total ban on tobaccoadvertising in the European Community ran into oppositionfrom four member nations today, virtually ensuring themeasure will not pass.   At a meeting of health ministers, Britain, Denmark,Germany and the Netherlands criticized the plan as anineffective way to curb smoking and an infringement onadvertising freedom.</LP><TEXT>   Opposition from those nations would be enough to defeatthe proposal when it comes up for a final vote later thisyear or in 1992.   The EC Commission, the trade bloc's administrative body,proposed the ban last month as a way to cut smoking-relatedillness and standardize advertising rules across its 12member sates. The commission wants to prohibit all tobaccoadvertising in the press, on billboards and elsewhere and toban T-shirts, lighters or other non-tobacco products frombearing a tobacco company's trademark.   &quot;Bans and moralizing lectures are not what we need,&quot; saidDanish Health Minister Ester Larsen. &quot;We need education toreduce smoking and high pricing to discourage the purchase ofcigarettes.&quot;   The members of the European Community agreed last year toa ban on tobacco advertising on television. It takes effectOct. 1.</TEXT></DOC>